in EDGE, I have identified the following workaround (example, in a real scenario there would need to be a rule for each destination IP to its corresponding accessible IP in the case where DNS, objectstorage, and potentially other end-points are on different machines):

- on each NC, rules like this re-map destination IPs.  In my case, all FE services are on 2.0.0.1/5.0.0.1, so I only need one rule

{code}
iptables -t nat -A EUCA_NAT_PRE_POSTUSERHOOK -d 2.0.0.1/32 -j DNAT --to-destination 5.0.0.1
{code}

just a quick comment - for our 'ecc like' public cloud at coresite, the workaround as described is functioning.  Since that cloud has two OSG end-points, two rules are required to be statically set (in /etc/sysconfig/iptables) on all node controllers

{code}
-t nat -A EUCA_NAT_PRE_POSTUSERHOOK -d 192.168.248.25/32 -j DNAT --to-destination 173.205.188.41
-t nat -A EUCA_NAT_PRE_POSTUSERHOOK -d 192.168.248.27/32 -j DNAT --to-destination 173.205.188.43
{code}
